      <ITEM><ARTICLE predecessor='http://sunsite.uakom.sk/sunworldonline/swol-05-1999/swol-05-filesystem.html'><X><T>Getting to know the Solaris filesystem, part 2</T><A>http://sunsite.uakom.sk/sunworldonline/swol-06-1999/swol-06-filesystem2.html</A><L>en</L><F>HTML</F></X><AUTHOR><FIRSTNAME>Richard</FIRSTNAME><LASTNAME>McDougall</LASTNAME></AUTHOR><DATE><YEAR>1999</YEAR><MONTH>6</MONTH></DATE><COMMENT>The first part defines the IO characteristics impacting file system performance. The second part explains how to tune the file system for data-intensive sequential workloads: read ahead, write behind, write throttle, write alignment and journaling. The third part speaks quickly about data-intensive random workloads (mainly optimized by caching the file system, see next article).</COMMENT></ARTICLE></ITEM>
      <ITEM><ARTICLE predecessor='http://sunsite.uakom.sk/sunworldonline/swol-06-1999/swol-06-filesystem2.html'><X><T>Getting to know the Solaris filesystem, part 3</T><A>http://sunsite.uakom.sk/sunworldonline/swol-07-1999/swol-07-filesystem3.html</A><L>en</L><F>HTML</F></X><AUTHOR><FIRSTNAME>Richard</FIRSTNAME><LASTNAME>McDougall</LASTNAME></AUTHOR><DATE><YEAR>1999</YEAR><MONTH>7</MONTH></DATE><COMMENT>Richard explains how to tune the block buffer cache (used for inode and inderection blocks) and the virtual memory system (used to cache file data).</COMMENT></ARTICLE></ITEM>
